@Node film
                               Film at 11
                              by @{" Jim Meyer " link Jim}

June was not the kindest of months for Commodore International.  After
announcing a loss of $173 million for the quarter, Commodore's stock
promptly plummeted to a record low.  At least two articles in prominent
newspapers have proclaimed Commodore as being either mortally wounded or
as close to it as a company can get.  And to bring things a little closer
to home for the electronic community, there were layoffs at West Chester.
This made it all too real; people we knew were out of work.

The inevitable followed.  Prophesies of Commodore's imminent demise
abounded, along with the customary retelling of all that Commodore has
done wrong in the last seven years.  The pain was palpable, accompanied
by the gnawing feeling that we were all powerless to intervene.

But what's all the fuss about?  The Amiga is nothing more than a
collection of silicon and copper, hosed in a plastic case.  It's a
servant, an electronic errand boy, and nothing more, right?

I think I can count the number of people who really feel that way on one
hand.  But on the other hand, it's a true statement.  Yes, there are more
than a few of us who know the name of the Father of the Amiga, and even
the name of his late dog.  Some of us even know the maiden name of RJ
Mical's wife, or the original name of the Amiga.  And that, I suspect, is
what makes the Amiga different.

It wasn't designed by a nameless committee.  It didn't even have an easy
birth.  And it had sneaky messages buried in the operating system,
accessible only through a Byzantine series of keystrokes.

And the rumors of its death may have been greatly exxagerated.  After
Commodore reportedly came to terms with the money folks, the stock
rallied and jumped 20% in a single day.  So it appears that there still
is hope, after all.  But that hope, sources say, resides within something
that brings the Amiga full cycle:  a games console.  The CD32,
Commodore's entry into the hotly-contested Games arena, may well carry
with it the future of the Amiga.

May you live in interesting times.  That curse, borrowed from another
culture, seems to perfectly describe the climate in today's computer
industry.  First, IBM announced record losses.  Then Commodore, Dell, and
finally Apple.  Can't anybody here play this game?

Maybe not.  At Commodore, it's the company itself that is fighting for
survival, not the Amiga.  Irving Gould would probably drop production of
the Amiga in a heartbeat if he had any alternative.  It means nothing
more to him than numbers on a ledger sheet.  And Apple is adrift,
watching their newly-captured market share being won back by the Intel
behemoth. IBM, Compaq, Dell, and countless others are learning that
prospective customers care more about the appellation "PC" or perhaps
"Intel Inside" than they do about the name that precedes it.  It's a
sorry state of affairs, and it just may get worse.

WANTED:  A group of visionaries who have the capability to shape the face
of computing, define the cutting edge, and pursue the vision.  Must be
willing to start immediately.  The alternative?  Memorize the phrase
AUTOEXEC.BAT and repeat until your brain stops functioning.

