@Node Math
                             MathVision2.4
                    Math Tools for Creative Graphics
                           by @{" Sylvia Lutnes " link Syl}

I used to be good at math - I actually got an A in calculus in college -
but that was (((1*3)*10^2)+(6*7)) moons ago. I can still add and
subtract, but understanding wpix(px,py,min(rpix(px,py)+1,31)) seems a bit
beyond me these days. MathVision 2.4 allows you to explore math through
visual representation of functions. But if you, like me, don't have the
time to spend in REALLY figuring out what's going on, you can still
derive great pleasure from this complex program and create pictures for
use as @{" backdrops " system "WDisplay VPort:weave"} and brushmaps in other programs.

Many formulas/functions are included with the program and you can load
them up and change numbers, change SIN to COS, change resolution and
palette, or do whatever you'd like to create variety in the output
without even understanding the underlying structure. MathVision 2.4 has
AGA support, can save IFF24 pictures, and understands ARexx. Its
interface is direct and easy to get used to, though you really do need to
read the documentation to understand viewers and colors and hooks and
basically just what is going on. It uses Doug's Color Commander as its
palette tool, which is fascinating to play with but takes some time to
master.

There are other ways to make pretty pictures besides choosing the math
behind it and waiting for the finished product. MathVision allows you to
make brushes that are actually formulas in disguise. You can paint with a
mathematical brush as you would an IFF brush in DPaint. This is loads of
fun. In fact MV supplies a 'front-end' that has some of these brushes
already made up for you. Click the mouse-button and there's a spiral,
choose another brush and there's fireworks.

MV can build anims with included utilities and do wipes and warps and
morphs (though the morph tool will only be sent upon registration). I
received one of the first non-beta releases and there was a letter
included telling me to register because there are still some ARexx
scripts and complete documentation that will be sent to registered users.
For now, there is just a 2.4 addendum to the spiral bound manual.

I had few problems with MV, except for its complexity. One major
annoyance is that AGA pictures saved out of MathVision often crash
Viewtek, crash DOpus, in fact crash the Amiga when you try to view them.
The workaround for now is to load them into AdPro/MP and save them out
again. DPaint loads them fine but ignores whatever is in the IFF file and
writes it back out the same way. I'm sure this will be addressed soon.

MV is an extremely powerful tool. If there's any aspect of the output you
wish to control you can. Of course, the best use will be made of the
program if you approach it from the mathematical side. There is enough in
here, however, to please even the math klutzes of the world who have a
bit of time and patience.

MathVision2.4
Seven Seas Software
P.O. Box 1451
Port Townsend  WA 98368
(206) 385-1956 $223

