@Node CED

                          Cygnus Ed (CED)
                         by @{" Kevin Ferlazzo " link Kevin}

Cygnus ED (CED) v3.5 is a full-featured text editor designed for
high-performance text entry.  It provides many of the basic features that
you expect in a word processor, but without giving up speed and ease of
use. @{" CED " system "WDisplay VPort:CEDscreen"} really shines as a programmer's editor, which makes it extremely
useful.  Included with CED are three other programs to make life easier:
ED (an optional front-end for CED), MetaMac (a macro editor), and
RecoverCEDFiles (for when Mr. Murphy strikes).  Also included are several
useful ARexx scripts.

CED runs on any Amiga using WB 1.3 or later, with at least 512K of
memory. For best utility, I recommend more memory, and a hard drive.  I
recommend this because of my tendency to open _lots_ of CED editor views
(a major convenience, by the way).  CED runs from either the CLI/Shell or
from Workbench.  ARexx support is built-in, allowing the user to write
scripts to automate any function in CED they want to.

CED is instaled via the Commodore Installer program, which makes it a
breeze to do.  Of course, make a backup of the CED distribution diskette
first, and then install from the backup.  Remember Mr. Murphy.

CED is now fully localized under WB 2.04 and up, with Locale file support
for English and German (Deutsch) provided.  CED uses the ASL system
standard file, font, and screen mode requesters under WB 2.04 and up.

---- Using CED ----

Using CED to edit your User-Startup, read a capture file from your
favorite online service, or write letters to Mom is easy.  From
WorkBench, select the icon for CED (or ED) and then <shift-click> on the
icons of the files you want to edit.  Or, from a CLI or Shell, type in
"ED filename" and CED will load the file you refer to (sans quotes, of
course).  Loading multiple files at once is easy; just type in "ED
filename1 filename2 filename3", etc.

A separate CED view opens for each file.  A view is that portion of a
file on the screen at any one time.  Each view has its own title bar,
display area, and (if you want) a scroll bar, with each view controlled
independently of any other view.  Just scroll to where you want to begin,
and start editing.  Views stack one on top of another (you can't have
views side by side).  In fact, CED allows you to have so many views that
it can get downright confusing!  The maximum number of views that CED
allows is up to 30 on a screen (or only as many your screen height will
allow), but CED allows you to spawn additional CED screens, each of which
can have 30 views.

All the functions you would expect of a first class text editor are in
CED, including cut and paste, search and replace (with history!),
auto-saving, background printing, macros, ARexx support, and undo.  Other
useful options are fixed-width font support, word wrap, centering lines,
opening on any public screen (under WB 2.04 and up only), and skipping
from one token (defined as a parenthesis '( )', bracket '[ ]', brace '{
}' or C comment mark '/* */') to its matching token.

A key feature of CED is that it supports both independent and cooperating
views, where 'independent' views are of different files, and
'cooperating' views are of the same file.  Using cooperating views allows
you to, for instance, have a function call and its definition on your
monitor simultaneously, even if they are at opposite ends of a huge file.

CED allows you to have multiple configurations, for different types of
files.  For instance, when editing C source files I use one set of macros
and tab settings.  When editing .doc or .txt files I use wholly different
macros and settings.

The ARexx capabilities of CED have been enhanced from earlier versions,
and previous owners of CED will be greatly pleased to hear that the
manual has been completely rewritten.  :) CED has over one hundred ARexx
commands (described in over 45 pages in the manual).

The macro abilities of CED have been greatly enhanced over earlier
versions, giving users the ability to create macros that will enter data
into any of CED's requesters.  So, for example, you can create a macro
that will enter into a search requester text that you have marked, and
then execute the search for you.

---- MetaMac ----

MetaMac answers a problem that earlier versions of CED had.  While CED
always allowed users to enter macros, it was impossible to edit them
without re-entering them from scratch.  MM is a stand-alone macro editor
that allows you to edit or create CED macros.  MM opens two windows on
the WorkBench, one that contains a listing of the macros saved in a
particular configuration, and one that shows you what commands the
selected macro contains at present.  MM allows you to put into your
macros virtually all the menu functions of CED, simply by selecting them
off MM's menus (CED menus are duplicated within MM).

MM and ARexx together allow CED to emulate virtually any other editor
available on the Amiga.  For instance, MM can bind to the sequence
<Ctrl-k><Ctrl-b> the command to start marking text.

---- RecoverCEDFiles ----

RecoverCEDFiles allows you to recover files that would have otherwise
been lost to a guru, recoverable alert, or a software failure.  After a
warm-boot, RCF searches all system memory looking for files that CED was
editing at the time of the crash.  If it finds a file in memory, RCF
reports which file it found, the file size, and how many changes had been
made to the file between the time it was last saved and the crash.  If
you wish to save it, a standard CED file requester saves the data.  RCF
should be run immediately after warm-booting your Amiga, in fact, the
best strategy is to interrupt the boot by using a <Ctrl-d> and then run
RCF! In combination with CED's Auto-Save abilities, it becomes very
difficult to lose important files that you are editing.

CED was written by Mr. Bruce Dawson, of CygnusSoft Software, and is
available now from ASDG, Incorporated.  List price of CED v3.5 is
$119.95, but previous owners may upgrade for only $35.

