@Node color

                      Migraph Colorburst Hand Scanner
                                by @{" Nick Cook " link Nick}

The ColorBurst is Migraph's new color hand scanner for the Amiga. To use
it, you'll need at least 2 megs of RAM, and WorkBench 1.3 or higher.
Migraph recommends an accelerated machine, 4 megs of RAM and a hard
drive. The package includes the scanner, power supply, interface box, and
the software program ColorKit.

ColorBurst scans from 50 to 400 dots per inch (dpi) in five modes:
 o Super Color (SCG), which reads up to 262,144 colors (e.g., the
   new AGA modes, although non-AGA machines can employ this mode)
 o Color (SC), which reads up to 4096 colors (the original HAM mode)
 o Monochrome Grey (MG), which reads true 64 resolution greyscale
 o Dithered Color (D), which reads 8 colors and uses one of three
   dither patterns to create the color image
 o Monochrome Text (T), is used for black and white art work and
   text

Installing ColorBurst is not difficult, but it is different than
Migraph's black and white scanner. While the latter could function
through a switch box, the former cannot. ColorBurst's interface box must
be plugged directly into the parallel port. This can be performed with
the Amiga's power on without frying any chips, according to the manual.
(I haven't tried that yet. Call me chicken.) The direct port access is
somewhat of a hassle, but the interface is attached to its plug via a
short length of ribbon cable. At least you don't have to wrestle your
Amiga around to get clearance for the three inch length of the interface
box. The power supply and the scanner are plugged into the interface.

The hefty scanner comes in a flat black case, with two sets of switches
on either side to control scan mode, pattern, DPI, and contrast. The
button to start a scan is on top, a somewhat inconvenient spot when
compared against its "thumb" location on the side of Migraph's black and
white scanner. Given the need for the interface to plug directly into the
Amiga, the scanner comes with a 5 foot connecting cable. A window allows
you to position materials accurately. The scanner's 5 inch head is a
different size than the black and white unit, so it won't fit the
templates for products such as the Scan:Align tray or Migraph's own
MergeIt tray.

The color unit requires different care and feeding than the black and
white scanner. ColorBurst incorporates a fluorescent scanner lamp which
must be warmed-up for at least two minutes at the start of a session, and
for at least 30 seconds prior to any scan. A progression bar counts down
the 30 second warm-up time whenever "Scan" is selected. You can abort
this warm-up period if you wish by a button click. Unfortunately, the
scanner does not automatically shut off. Once the lamp comes on, it stays
on until the scan sequence is performed: click on scan button, then hit
any key on the Amiga. If you forget to do this, and leave the lamp on for
longer than 10 minutes, the scanner overheats and affects image quality.
A software "nag" feature would be handy.

ColorKit software installation is a snap. An icon driven script places
Migraph's fonts in the appropriate library. The program is copied by
simply dragging the icon to its destination. The software is a front end
for the scanner only, and lacks the paint and processing functions of its
sister program, TouchUp. The uncluttered interface consists of only four
icons, other than the quit and depth gadget. These icons also have
keyboard equivalents.

Scanner settings for mode, DPI and length are selected by clicking the
second icon's requester. The mode and DPI settings must match the
switches on the scanner, otherwise especially ugly images result.
Unfortunately, the software does not read the scanning unit's settings.
The user must make the settings manually on both the scanner and
software. Since some modes, such as SCG, suck up memory faster than
Dracula in a bloodbank, the Scan Setting requester provides a listing of
currently available RAM, as well as how much RAM is needed. This allows
you to make any adjustments prior to attempting the scan.

You may be initially surprised to see a blank screen after completing a
scan. This is because ColorKit is waiting for specific instructions on
how to display the raw data. Based on the scan mode, the program offers
quite a few options beyond paper or plastic:

       o Hires or Lores, Standard or Overscan
       o Interlaced or not, NTSC or PAL
       o 2, 8, 16, 32, 64 or 256 (AGA) colors
       o HAM-6, HAM-6 CR (or "crunched"; this option discards
         every other horizontal pixel to get the picture square again)
       o For AGA machines, HAM-8
       o 16 greyscale for all Amigas, 256 Grey for AGA Amigas
       o Error correction, and High quality (for AGA) is also available.

After selecting display options, ColorKit reduces colors, constructs
histograms, and creates the image on the screen. Time to get a cup of
coffee. On my A3000, a HAM-6 picture took approximately a minute and a
half to complete. On slower machines, go get a cup of coffee and watch
Oprah. The manual contains several references to speed and processors.

How did the displays look? On my stock 1084S monitor, not bad. The
greyscale is excellent. Scanning color pictures and reducing them to
black and white images used to remind me of a hillbilly stuffed into a
too-small- suit: more information than the package can hold. With the
ColorBurst, however, scanning color images in greyscale results in an
excellent quality image, almost as though the original was in black and
white. The HAM-6 CR does not distort the image. HAM-6 still tends to
fringe, and the color reduction casts a tint to the image. For example, a
scanned photo of a model standing in a meadow rendered a greenish tinge
to the model's skin tone. The display function certainly shouldn't be
used as conversion software, either. If you want proof, just display a
HAM image as Lores 32 color. Looks like the latest VGA to LORES game
conversion, huh? The manual recommends the Dithered color setting only if
you find yourself in a low memory or limited disk space situation. This
is for good reason: the dithered images are flat ugly.

A number of options are available when saving a file. Along with the
selections outlined above, a SCG image can be saved as 24 bit. Not that
ColorKit is somehow vaulting over hardware, but rather the 18 bit SCG
image is stored in a 24-bit database. This permits the scanned image to
be imported into programs such as ADPro or ImageMaster for further image
processing. Other aspects of the image, such as X/Y offset, width,
height, and saving the full image versus the screen, can be altered.

A ColorKit bug pops up in the save function: you play hide-and-go-seek
with the file requester. After setting the save parameters, and clicking
OK, a grey screen covers the lower three fourths of the image. I assume
this is the background for the file requester. Except the requester is
AWOL. By toggling to the Workbench screen (left Amiga M), you'll find the
file requester patiently waiting. It works normally, but after you save
your image, you need to flip the screen back into ColorKit (via left
Amiga N). According to Migraph, this is due to a bug in the Commodore's
ASL, and won't occur if your running Workbench 2.1/3.0. A ReadMe file
notes that two feature - - scrolling the image with the mouse and
multiple error correction/dither choices - - are not implemented in this
version. A ColorKit update which fixes these bugs and offers new features
is promised in July.

The 52 page, indexed manual gets the job done; its organized well and the
writing is not too obtuse. It would have been nice, though, to provide
the Resolution Settings chart on either a separate reference card or on
the last page of the manual. Currently it sits on page 23, requiring you
to thumb through the manual when setting up a scan.

ColorBurst is a flexible unit, useful for DTP, OCR, and to a lesser
extent, in video or multimedia. The ColorKit software, although lacking
the power of TouchUp, is adequate for getting an image into your Amiga. I
have had no complaints with Migraph's customer service over the years
I've dealt with them (they've phoned me after I've sent in bug reports).
If you're looking for color hand scanner, check out ColorBurst.

