@Node Vision

                   Visionaire-A Morphing Alternative
                            by @{" William Graham " link Bill}

Amiga users have the luxury of being able to choose from several 2D
morphing programs. However, this type of software is no longer causing
the level of excitement it did when first released. 2D morphing is
accepted as a standard tool for videographers, animators, and those
people developing multimedia applications. Though the excitement has died
down a bit, almost everyone agrees that this type of software has
unleashed a fresh new wave of creativity. It is, for the most part, easy
to use and understand, and does not have nearly the steep learning curve
that 3D graphics and animation have, for example.

So yet another 2D morphing program is not about to make cover stories for
Amiga magazines, one would think. "After all," the jaded Amiga artist may
say, "so there's another 2D morphing program.  You've seen one, you've
seen them all." You already own one, maybe two, they work pretty much the
same, save maybe for some minor qualitative differences. They all seem to
cost less than $200. They all are (usually) bundled as part of another
image processing program.

But there is another kid on the block. It is indeed another 2D morphing
program, and works similarly to the others, at least at first......

Visionaire. A 2D morphing program from Impulse,Inc. Visionaire was
written in Brazil, where it is known as MorphOs (not to be confused with
MorphUs, also available from Impulse) and was written by Bruno Costa and
Lucia Darsa. Impulse is marketing the product in the U.S.

Visionaire does indeed have the standard From and To windows. It will
handle the three basic types of morphing, warping a still, morphing one
still to another, and morphing one sequence of frames to another sequence
of frames. Editing is accomplished by moving the points of a grid
superimposed over the images. Visionaire does support AGA, in both
editing and output. For ECS users, you have the choice of on-the-fly
greyscale (8 level) conversion of your images, or hi-res color (16
colors) conversion that change to accommodate the image you are working
on when editing. Output is either 24 bit IFF or standard Amiga
resolutions. Impulse's proprietary format, RGB8, is NOT supported.

Visionaire ships with an outstanding 175 page manual, that, aside from a
very few typos, is as clear and understandable as any software manual I
have seen. Obviously, it was not written by Impulse. There are some very
fine tutorials, along with a nicely written index. Visionaire is not copy
protected, and ships with two disks, the program disk and an example/
tutorial disk. Hard drive installation is effortless.

Although Visionaire is a 2D morphing program, and though the interface
seems very similar to other software of that type, there are some very
big differences. The first and most important is the use of Mixers.
Mixers are a way of controlling the rate of morphing in a sequence of
images. Mixers are used for both Color and Shape morphing, which can be
handled separately in Visionaire. Furthermore, each and every editing
point can have its own separate Mixer for both Color and Shape. This
means that you have complete control over the progress of the morph for
every part of the image. You can, for instance, in a morph between two
faces, have the nose morph first, then the mouth, then the rest of the
image. Or you could have eye color morph before the shape of the eyes
themselves.

Mixers are very simple to use. They are represented on screen as a box
with a horizontal and a vertical line in the middle. The horizontal axis
represents the output frames from left to right, and the vertical axis is
the percentage of transformation with the bottom being all From image,
top being all To image. Overlaid is a diagonal line (the default) from
bottom left to upper right. This third line is actually a type of spline
or curve that can be manipulated much like those in a structured drawing
program. The shape of the curve determines the "bias" of the morph for
that area. Color and Shape mixers work identically. There is a global
Color and Shape mixer as well. Mixers can be copied from one area to
another, and saved for reuse. The "border" between Mixer areas is
smoothly interpolated. The Mixer tutorial has you morphing a woman to a
cheetah, using Mixers to have the woman's hair linger for a few frames on
the cheetah, resulting in a mindblowing morph. The ability to micro-
control all parts of an image, or sequence of images, in time during a
morph has to be experienced to be appreciated. The rendered output is as
good as any I've seen, and is quite fast, depending on the number of
mixers in use, as well as number of editing points.

Visionaire also supports the use of a sequence of greyscale pictures that
are used as Alpha channels. In this way, it is possible to render 2 or
more morphs, then composite them together through alpha channels.
Similarly, you could mask several sequences of images together also.

As with other 2D morphing software, Visionaire will morph two different
sequences of images. If you've ever tried this, you know it takes a lot
of work. It takes a lot of work with Visionaire also, but some help is
provided through the use of the keyframe concept. If you're working with
two sequences of 100 frames each, for instance, you do not have to edit
the mesh for each and every frame. You can edit every 5th, or 10, or
whatever provides the best results. Visionaire will smoothly interpolate
the "in between" frames. Some other morphing  programs support a keyframe
concept also, but with Visionaire there is one major difference. The
keyframes of the two sequences DO NOT have to be the same!! This is real
morphing power, folks! Keep in mind the Mixer concept when imagining the
kind of morphing you can do here!

ARexx support is extensive, with 77 commands, including the ability to
modify Mixers. Visionaire comes with several scripts that can be called
from within the program. ARexx scripts can also be assigned to F keys,
thereby automating many processes.

Visionaire is completely configurable, from screen colors used to
hotkeys. All in all this is a very nice piece of work. I have had a few
crashes, but I suspect my PP&S '040 may have something to do with it. My
local dealer sells Visionaire for $149.00. If you are a registered
Imagine user, you can get it for $59.00, a super deal. Even with the
occasional crash I would have to recommend this to the Amiga artist who
wants to expand their creative options.

For more information contact:
