@Node dopus

                               DOpus Tricks
                               by @{" Jim Meyer " link Jim}

Directory Opus - DOpus, to old friends - is by far the most popular
directory utility ever released for the Amiga.  With a powerful set of
built-in commands, an ARexx port, and almost infinite configurability,
DOpus provides an alternate workplace, one that is unique for each user.

As powerful as DOpus is, however, it can be a bit intimidating.  Some
users go through the basic steps of configuration and stop there, using
DOpus only as a souped-up directory utility.  It can be much more than
that, though.  All you need to do is learn a few of the basics.  With
that in mind, I'll tackle some of the most frequent requests for DOpus
scripts.

Question:  How can I get DOpus to sort directories differently?  I don't
always want an alphabetic sort; sometimes I want files listed by date or
size, but I don't want to change the default each time.

Answer:  The key is the MODIFY command.  This command lets you change the
manner in which most DOpus commands operate, either permanently or
temporarily.  In this case, we need to change the sort method.  The
command to do this is MODIFY SORTMETHOD.  We'll create a series of
buttons that let you change to any of 4 sort methods.

1 - Open the Configuration screen, and select Buttons.

2 - When the Button bank screen displays, click on an empty button.  If
there aren't any, select the next bank.  This brings up the @{" Edit Button " system "WDisplay VPort:dopus1.pic" }
screen.  If you need any help at this point, click on the question mark
at the top of the screen.

3 - Give the button a name in the Name field (like DateSort, for the
first example), and click on New E ntry. The Command Entry gadget will
become active.

4 - We're using DOpus commands for these examples.  The Command Entry
gadget should come up with "Command" as the active mode, as opposed to
AmigaDOS or ARexx.  If not, click on the gadget until it reads Command.

5 - Now, enter the actual commands.  After each command is entered, hit
Return and click on New Entry to enter the next command.  For the first
example, Sort by Date, you'll need the following commands: (Note that
COMMAND refers to the mode; do NOT type it!)

COMMAND Remember COMMAND Modify SortMethod -1 3 COMMAND Rescan

The first command, Remember, tells DOpus that this is a temporary
modification.  The second command uses two arguments to tell DOpus that
this operation is to be performed on the active window (-1) and that the
SortMethod should be changed to DateStamp. (3)

NOTE:  The second parameter indicates the number of the sort item in the
configuration list (Operation, List Format) DOpus keeps.  If you have the
items listed in any order other than the default, the 3 will refer to the
fourth item in the list.  (The list starts at 0.)

Use the same template to create buttons for sorts based on size,
filetype, and name.  Just change the second parameter in the Modify
SortMethod command.

Now that ViewPort is available in an AmigaGuide version, you might want
to give DOpus the capability to automatically detect .guide files and
take the appropriate action.  Since AmigaGuide files always begin with
'@database', we can define a new file class.  Again, bring up the
configuration editor.

1 - Select Filetypes.  This brings up the @{" Filetype Configuration " system "WDisplay VPort:dopus2.pic"} screen.
You'll see a list of filetype actions; these are predefined commands
given to DOpus when you invoke the "auto" function by double-clicking or
click-m-clicking on a file name.  (There are other ways to invoke this
function; consult your DOpus manual.)

2 - We want to add an entirely new class, so select New... from the
Classes menu.  This brings up the "file class edit" screen.  It may look
blank and formidable, but that's just a ruse.  DOpus provides a lot of
help for you. At the top of the screen, you'll see a gadget labeled "File
viewer."  This is useful if you don't know how to identify a particular
file type; click on the gadget and a file requester will display.  Use
the requester to locate the type of file you want to define, and DOpus
will display it for you, in hex or decimal.  If you select an AmigaGuide
file, for example, you'll see that it begins with @database or @Database.

3 - Armed with this knowledge, we can proceed.  Give the file class a
name (AmigaGuide is fine) and a file ID (GUIDE will do).  These are just
identifiers for your use.  The names aren't critical.

4 - Now, we have to tell DOpus how to find this kind of file.  Click on
the New Entry button, near the bottom of the screen.  DOpus will create a
line for you, starting with the word MATCH.  This is the default action.
There are others, but we want MATCH.

5 - Click on the text gadget just above the row of buttons.  This is
where you'll type the phrase that DOpus will look for to identify this
file class.  Type @?atabase.  The question mark allows DOpus to match
either "@Database" or "@database".  Since this search is case-sensitive,
we want to allow for both possibilities.

6 - Click on OK.  You'll be returned to the Filetype configuration
screen. The filetype is now defined, but there's no action to go with it.
To add an action, click on the New button and select the filetype you've
just defined.  When the next screen displays, select an event from the
Events... gadget.  I find Double-click to be the most convenient, but you
should choose whatever suits your style.

7 - We're almost home.  Click on the New Entry button.  DOpus will supply
you with the default mode, Command.  We don't want that, though. Click on
the mode selector gadget until it reads AmigaDOS.

8 - Type "AmigaGuide {f}" in the string gadget.  If AmigaGuide is NOT in
your normal search path, supply the full path name.  For example,
SYS:Utilities/AmigaGuide {f}.

9 - Click on OK.  When the Filetype configuration screen displays, select
Save from the Configure menu.  And that's all there is to it!  You can
now invoke AmigaGuide automatically whenever you double-click (or take
whatever action you've defined) on an AmigaGuide file!

Once you get DOpus configured to your liking, you may find yourself
spending more time in DOpus than in Workbench.  This doesn't mean that
you have to give up the amenities of the Workbench screen, though.  Any
program that will open on a public screen can open up on a DOpus screen.
For this example, we'll create a button that opens a Shell on a DOpus
screen.

1 - Call up the configuration program and select Buttons.  Pick a
conveniently empty button and click on it.

2 - Give the button a name and click on the New Entry button.

3 - Click on the Mode gadget until it cycles to AmigaDOS.

4 - All of the magic is contained in the window specification.  The
template for the NewShell command is:

 NEWSHELL [<window specification>] [FROM <filename>]

 The template for <window specification> is:

 CON:x/y/width/height/title/options

The options are the tricky part.  If you want to open a shell on a public
screen, you must use the SCREEN option.  (And, according to Andy Finkel,
the SCREEN option must be last, due to a bug in the NewShell command.)
So, to open a shell 10 pixels from the left, 10 pixels from the top, 300
pixels wide, 100 pixels high, with a title of DOpusShell and a close
gadget, you would use the following command:

 AmigaDOS  NewShell CON:10/10/300/100/DOpusShell/CLOSE/SCREEN{p}

Note that you don't type AmigaDOS; DOpus supplies that for you.  The {p}
in the command line instructs DOpus to enter the name of its public
screen.

5 - That's all there is to it.  Click on OK, and select Save from the
Configure menu.

Of course, you don't have to run DOpus as a separate screen.  You can run
it as a Workbench window, and you can change between configurations at
will.  All you need is one more button!  Here's the commands for two
buttons to change DOpus from opening on a full-length Workbench clone
screen to a half-height window on Workbench itself, and back.

1 - Call up the Configuration editor one more time, select Buttons, and
pick an appropriately blank button.

2 - We'll use a DOpus command this time, so make sure the Mode gadget is
set to Command.  The commands to instruct DOpus to reopen as a
half-height window ON the Workbench screen are shown below.  Remember,
COMMAND is supplied by DOpus; don't type it in.

 COMMAND Remember
 COMMAND MODIFY ScreenMode 1
 COMMAND MODIFY ScreenFlags 4
 COMMAND Redraw

The first line instructs DOpus to remember its current state.  The second
line tells DOpus that we want it to open on Workbench's screen.  The
third line calls for a half-height screen, and the last command caused
DOpus to close and reopen in the new configuration.

Because we used the Remember command, we can return to the previous
setting with these two commands:

 COMMAND Restore
 COMMAND Redraw

However, you should note that Restore will cause DOpus to revert either
to the settings as of the last Remember command, or - if no Remember
command has been issued - to the default settings.

As you have seen, getting DOpus to do what you want isn't difficult.  The
instructions tend to be simple and brief.  In fact, the hardest part can
be finding the information in the manual, which is woefully short on
examples.  But once you get over the initial hurdle, you can begin to
exploit the full potential of DOpus.  And that's when the fun really
starts!

