                             The Uploads of June
                                by @{" Nick Cook " link Nick}

June may be busting out all over, but GEnie Amigans are still taking the
time to upload, upload, and upload! From the library this month...

*I CODE THE SONGS THAT MAKE MY AMIGA SING...*

19655 ASOLIDBREAKFAST.LHA 19654 DARKNESS&LIGHT.LHA 19653
MEDIEVALLIGHTS.LHA 19601 BLOODONTHER.LHA 19652 LUTHHYMNS.LHA 19600
BEAUTY.LHA 19911 URALVOLGA.LHA 19724 CALIBRA.LHA

While taste in music is personal, I enjoy mods that differ from the usual
pop hip hop techno rave rap retro 70s disco dance new age stuff. "A Solid
Breakfast" is listed in the Library as a "silly" mod. No false
advertising here; its a fun, up tempo work with a hint of the country
swing sound. Just the thing to play after reading about Commodore's
plunging stock prices. David Turner's "Darkness_&_Light" is a moody,
atmospheric 20 minute epic that swirls between ominous and affirmation.
Its like listening to a soundtrack from a sword and sorcery film. A
shorter Turner mod, "Medieval Lights", evokes images of a magical gnome's
apparatus-filled cave. Despite the title, Dr. Awesome's "Blood on the R"
(yep, that's the way it unarchives --I guess we'll never know what got
messy) is a charming chamber piece, perhaps something you'd hear on a
pre-guillotine visit to Marie Antoinette's court. "LuthHymms" is Dave
Reynolds' collection of four circa 1700s Lutheran hymns arranged for MED.
"Beauty" reminds one of Mandheim Steamroller: a Baroque-like theme played
on guitar and backed by a strong drum track. This mod is ideal for
multimedia production background music. "Ural Volga" sounds like a
Lawrence Welk polka on speed, and perhaps is one of the few mods which
make you laugh out loud. "Calibra" won first place at the Gathering. For
good reason. This jazz arrangement employs some of the best sampled
instruments I've ever heard on the Amiga. The resulting music sounds like
its coming straight off a CD. Great for music lovers, and a wonderful
addition to Amiga "brag" disks.

*LET THE GAMES BEGIN!*

19587 NETHACK31-1.LHA 19591 NETHACK31-2.LHA

After listening to all that medieval music, you may want to hobnob with
some wizards, elves, and, ah, kittens. NetHack is cross platform,
multi-level "Dungeons and Dragons" type game. Its a _huge_ two part
download. Workbench 1.2 + and at least 2 megs of RAM is required to play.
Over 3 megs of free hard drive space is recommended, or 4 floppies and
two drives can be used. Although the latter setup is acceptable, be
prepared for alotta disk swaps (BTW: one floppy should be labelled
"levels", not, as the ReadMe files states, "NHLevels"). Don't even think
about NetHack on a single floppy drive system; your patience will be
sorely tried, not to mention your wrist.  The interface is standard
Workbench with ascii graphics and text that reads a bit like the old
Adventure Construction Kit; e.g. "The bat bites you", "The rock hits you."

What the game lacks in bells and whistles, it makes up in depth. You can
chose to be one of several characters (I picked the anthropologist, and
my inventory included a bullwhip and brown fedora!), or let the computer
randomly select one for you. A complete guidebook explains the other
characters, traits, spells and locations. On line help is available and
welcome (a request for NetHack's programmers: how about an AmigaGuide
version of Help and the guidebook?).

19603 WIBBLEWORLDGIDDY.DMS Wibble World Giddy (say that five times fast)
is a cute British PD platform game, great for kids of all ages. You guide
Giddy, a rather peculiar, egg- shaped creature wearing a straw hat, on
his way home, gathering spinning coins and solving puzzles en route.
There's lots of smart aleck humor in this game: Giddy can pick up an
Atari ST (out of a trash can), graffiti spells out "boring, eh?", and a
Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtle tends shop. If Giddy encounters some dangers,
he doesn't "die", but rather goes "splat". The game world brims with
bright, animated graphics, the requisite rainbow sky background and
determinedly punchy music. Joystick control is good. The sometimes
controversial ".DMS" file compression is used on this file, so be
prepared to abandon all logic. When .DMS starts unpacking Wibble World
Giddy, it notes a non-standard boot block. Ignore it. After unpacking the
disk, .DMS discovers another error (apparently due to modem padding),
declares it fatal, then exits. Ignore it. If you double click the new
disk's icon, it will show 0% full. Ignore it. A "dir" command on the new
disk will reveal nothing. Ignore it. Boot off of the Wibble World Giddy,
and the game works. Since Giddy comes to us from overseas, its in PAL.
Giddy therefore disappears suddenly into some pits that are off the
bottom of the screen.

19762 STARSHIP20.LHA Don't think much of Captains Kirk and Picard? Think
that you can handle a starship better than those bus drivers? Here's your
chance. Starship 2.0 is an nearly commercial level simulator (And the
author, Russ Grasso, only wants $5! What a deal!). This is a *huge*
download! After unpacking, Starship 2.0 takes up more than 880K. Alas,
the NoteBook format manual and/or viewer refused to work for me, so I was
flying blind. The program features background sound effects (you can
choose music instead, but stick with the sound effects), multiple
windows, data readouts, etc. I'm not technically oriented, so I have no
idea whether the physics and concepts behind Starship are accurate or not
(admittedly a big part of simulations), but they certainly sound
impressive! This thing is slick, slick, slick!

19844 POPWORLDS2.LHA Dig out that old Populous game! The creative
Jennifer Reitz (of Accursed Toys) has designed some custom worlds, many
from cult sci-fi. How about a battle between ants and people, a la THEM!
Or aliens and arctic scientists from THE THING? Pretend you're a young
Steve McQueen fighting THE BLOB! There's even a SPACE:1999 set!
Instructions are included for integrating these custom worlds into the
Populous game.

*I'LL TAKE AMIGA UTILITIES FOR $20 PLEASE, ALEX.*

19599 TEXTRA14.LHA The much reviled "Ed" and "Edit" Workbench programs
touched off a cottage industry in text editors. David Hass' contribution
is Textra 1.4. This easy-to-use program is packed with features such as
background printing, ARexx, Undo, multiple windows in different fonts,
cut and paste between windows, a 'mouse-drag-select' function, as well as
on line help. Special programmers functions include angle and bracket
matching. As I merrily typed into column 84, I discovered with some
dismay that Textra lacks word wrap. While the demo version is completely
functional, $25 gets you a registered version which allows you to be free
from the minute's worth of nag screens.

19732 NOTEIT!.LHA 19752 TRASHCANICON.LHA 19900 CLICKDEPTH10.LHA Here's a
few nifty, small 2.0 + utilities to stuff in your overloaded WBStartup
drawer. NoteIt!, by Ryan J. Bruner, is an electronic version of those
yellow sticky notes. It opens a small window on the Workbench screen,
allowing you to type in your flashes of inspiration or shopping list. The
program saves your notes between power cycles or after approximately 10
seconds of inactivity. An iconify feature or Hot Keys would be a nice
addition to the next version. You don't have to empty the trash anymore
with TrashIcon. Mark McPherson's handy program places an icon at a
user-defined Workbench position, and deletes all files that are dragged
onto it. But wait, there's more! By setting tooltypes, TrashIcon will (or
won't) request confirmation before deleting a file, and can even perform
disk formats. ClickDepth V1.0, by Anders Hammarquist, a small, 2K
commodity that allows you to depth-arrange windows using the mouse and
(opional) qualifiers. For some reason, when I set up ClickDepth, it
operated opposite of what the docs said, but it worked nonetheless. Drop
this in WPStartup drawer if you usually leave a lot of windows open on
your Workbench.

19737 MULTIAPP.LHA MultiApp, by Claude Müller, places an AppIcon on your
Workbench. Drag a file icon onto the AppIcon, and MultiApp recognizes the
file as one of the user-defined types and executes a command.  For
example, drag the icon of an IFF-picture onto MultiApp's AppIcon.
MultiApp detects the IFF-ILBM format and shows the picture with a
user-defined viewer. GEnie member Malcom Allen helpfully includes a small
readme file on MultiApp's known bugs: it doesn't like file names with
spaces in them, and it ocassionally trashes its own config file. Setting
up MultiApp reminded me of setting up Tool Manager: despite printing out
the concise docs, the program still requires some intuitive "fiddling",
primarily as regards to paths, to get it up and running.

19831 DISKSALV2.LHA DiskSalv, Dave Haynie's long running disk salvage
program, is now out in a new version. It recovers data from a disk in
"severe trouble" (the ones that I let become cat toys), fixes many of the
problems directly on the problem disk, and locates valid partitions on a
disk with an unknown layout or damaged rigid disk block.  Version 2
supports all AmigaDOS file systems through 3.0. An appreciated
improvement is the point and click interface. For $40, a user receives an
approximately 100 page professional quality printed manual, AmigaGuide
on-line manual, the latest version and a free upgrade. Although at
present the shareware and registered version of DiskSalv are the same,
Haynie writes, they may not always be. DiskSalv is one of those "must
haves".

19564 AII_V135.LHA From the Land Down Under comes Archiving Intuition
Interface (AII), a workbench program that enables users to archive and
de-archive files using most of the various archivers around, without
needing to learn (or look up) multitudes of commands, what they stand
for, and type in CLI arguments. In other words, its mouse time. AII works
with Workbench 1.3 +, but requires ReqTools library (and according to the
docs, GadTools, but I don't have them and AII is working just fine). The
various archivers must be rounded up as well. Installation is a breeze
(drag the icon to the desired resting place), and creating the config.
file simply requires clicking on the archivers' names from their
directory. A minor annoyance is in the interface design: clickable
buttons are drawn the same as read-only boxes. AII is a utility that
makes life in the GEnie library easier!

* By the way - Here's a few tips on a some downloads:

19780 VIDEOTRACKER.LHA VideoTracker is a poor man's Deluxe Video: a way
to combine music and graphics. Apparently it doesn't like the '030: it
crashed on my 3000, but it ran on a 500. However, it gurued when I
attempted to load an example. Ah, well. Be prepared to spend some time
with this program.

19779 THEME_DREAM.MOD.LHA The mod Theme-Dream  requires a music player
that can handle PAL. In NTSC, the drum beat is "off".

*And you may need these files:

15924 DMS111.EXE (for Wibble World Giddy) 18984 REQTOOLSV21A.LHA (for
AII) 16895 LHA_138.RUN (for AII; perhaps the most common Amiga archiver)
18580 INFOZIP.LHA (for AII, but you may not need it) 19166 LX100.LHA (for
AII, but again, you may not need it)

We started with a song, so let's leave with a song: Summertime, and the
livin' is easy...

Enjoy!

