                        B-17 FLYING FORTRESS
                           by @{" David Moore " link David}

In the spring of 1942, the US 8th Air Force joined the RAF in the bombing
of Germany. While the RAF bombed under the protection of darkness, the
Americans decided that daylight bombing would produce more accurate
results. Because of the increased vulnerability of daylight bombing, the
aircraft the Americans chose to undertake this task would need to be very
heavily armed. Thus it was that the mainstay of the US 8th Air Force, the
B-17, was known to all as the Flying Fortress.

B-17 Flying Fortress from Microprose has finally touched down on the
Amiga and seems to have been worth the wait. The usual large Microprose
box contains the, again, usual large game manual, foldout B-17 poster,
three disks, and an Amiga specific technical supplement.

The manual I know has received criticism from some quarters for
containing too much information which is irrelevant to the game. The
chapters which I think they are referring to deal with the historical
background to the bombing campaign and the development of the B-17
itself. I felt that these chapters added great authenticity and
atmosphere and really put the game in context. One thing I was
disappointed with given the multitude of keyboard commands was the
absence of a keyboard overlay as provided with F-19, for example.
Although a keyboard reference chart is provided in the technical
supplement, it is a poor substitute.

On to the game itself. As the B17 carried a crew of ten, you are
encouraged to move from position to position, it is much closer to games
like Megafortress from 360 than a "normal" single seat flight sim. In
fact the flying only takes up a small amount of your time. As such games
like this deserve a new classification. Air battle simulator perhaps?

When the game loads up, there are some nice loading screens and music to
enjoy. Once past the obligatory copy protection, you are asked to select
your bomber from a choice of six on the roster screen. You can select any
of the six and reset it, which will enable you to select your own nose
art from a choice of cartoon characters [or scantily clad young ladies,
whichever you prefer!] You can also name your bomber as well.

Once this has been done, you can go onto the Ops room, where you can
assigned missions (the ultimate goal of the game is to complete a tour of
25 missions) or undergo some training - which would be advisable. You can
also view a photograph of your crew from which you can select a file on
each man giving you his skills ratings: Gunnery, Bombing, Technical,
Medical and Piloting. Obviously crew members will be better at his
speciality than any other, but should say the Navigator be injured, you
could check the stats to see who could his job at a lower level (when the
crew successfully complete a mission, their stats improve accordingly).
Should you be unfortunate to have a crew member killed, his replacement
will invariably be a rookie and you will have to nuture his skills in
exactly the same way, so obviously it is in your interest to look after
your crew. It is this aspect of the game which makes it stand out of
other games. You feel a sense of involvement with your crew.

When you are assigned a mission you can view reconnaissance film of the
targets which is very useful, as the target will look quite different
from 10,000 ft. Before you actually start the game proper, you can tailor
the difficulty, by setting up the quality of the enemy opposition and the
reliability of the bombs you will be dropping.

Once done, you begin the game in the Pilot's seat at your dispersal point
on the airfield. At each crew position, you can toggle between manual and
computer control (effectively, your crew member in that position). You
can involve yourself as much as you like. For the first training mission
you would probably be well advised watching what goes on during the
course of the mission. On takeoff and landing you will be occupied in the
pilots stations, the Navigator will be used throughout the mission, while
the gunners will come into their own repelling fighters over enemy
territory. All this is to allow the Bombardier to drop his bombs on the
right target. The graphics are well detailed, the rendition of the pilots
panels are particulary noteworthy. When the aircraft is viewed
externally, the gun turrets can be seen traversing, the gunners scanning
the skies for enemy aircraft. Indeed, there are a whole range of views to
experiment with. A particularly good view is a close up view of your
target, so you can see exactly where your bombs impact.

If you make the journey home and land successfully your crew improve,
promotions and decorations are on offer as well as coming on step closer
to the goal of 25 missions. I have only scratched the surface of the game
in this review. There is a rich depth of detail which will become
apparent to the player after extended use. B-17 can wholeheartedly be
recommended to the flight sim enthusiast.

