@Node Dune

                  DUNE II - THE BATTLE FOR ARRAKIS - VIRGIN
                             by @{" Derek Dela Fuente " link Derek}

Dune was visually one of the nicest looking games of the year with some
state of the art graphics and animation but to some critics the actual
game did not have enough depth or longevity. Dune II is written by
Westwood Studios, the team behind Eye of the Beholder 1 & 2 and Kyrandia.
The first Dune game was written by Kryo in France but the American
presentation is far removed from the first. It can be likened to Sim
City...in fact, Sim Sand could be a good title. The onus of the game is
very much on strategy and management with a heavy real-time combat
element. The view within the game is top down.

The introduction to Dune II is meant to give the player a brief bit of
background. Various animated sequences and synchronized music will build
the setting for the game. The player is then given three totally
different families or `Houses' to choose from and play. Each house has it
own personalities - Atreides, Ordod or Harkonnens. The intention, when
you are allied to one house, is gaining control of the planets most
valuable commodity - the drug, spice.

The core of Dune II's strategy element concerns the manufacture and
management of functional buildings such as spice refinement plants and
military and civilian units. In combat, players can set their forces in
motion and concentrate on the other aspects of play or closely control
individual units to utilise them to their best capability.

When the player chooses his House the other two will be generated by the
computer. These computer controlled houses display different
personalities and strategies. The variety of Houses and the ways to play
each will greatly enhance the game ensuring that the it is never the same.

If, for instance, you choose the house Atreides, you will play the good
guys in the game. This is a very idealistic house, run by honour codes
and utopian ideals. Due to these attributes, the Attreides will often
speak of their strengths and rarely of any weaknesses. The benefit of
this type of personality is that the honour and moral of their men is
unparalleled. Yet this also causes them to underestimate a situation or
enemy, believing that their superiority will prevail in any situation.

Throughout the game you will build, buy better equipment and generally
acquire more land. You may have just a small yard to start with. This
will require windtraps to be placed before you can start on the refinery.
Construction is a very important aspect of the game.

The player will have to create and maintain vast bases in each scenario.
To succeed at this task, the player will need to manage his resources
very wisely. Each building that is created is functional and each
performs a specific task: refine spice, produce military and civilian
units, construct other buildings, provide power, provide trade, etc.

The combat side to the game is in real-time, easily and quickly
manipulated via the mouse and is not turn-based. This real- time combat
adds intensity to the game and will keep the player's concentration high
throughout each scenario. The player can set his units in motion and
concentrate on the other features of the game. A menu will appear to help
the combat procedure: attack, defend or retreat can easily be executed.

The presentation to the game, especially the digitised voices and speech,
makes it very appealing. The digitised sound will bring battles to life
with the sound of guns booming and soldiers screaming. Each house has a
different digitised voice. One could have a woman's voice whilst the
other has a powerful man's voice giving the player a better understanding
and feel of what is happening.

The game has a very structured format. The process from starting to build
with concrete slabs to light factories with walls will become apparent
but much skill will be required to achieve your goals.

`Dune II' is a wholly more intriguing game than the original, requiring
tactical know-how as opposed to the puzzle- based, structured approach
required of `Dune I'. Highly recommended.

